South African White, Yellow Corn Gains, Following Advance by U.S Benchmark

-- B y   M k h u l u l i   M a n c o t y w a
-- 
2011-03-15T07:57:52Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-15/south-african-white-yellow-corn-gains-following-advance-by-u-s-benchmark.html
Corn prices rose in  South Africa ,
following a gain in  Chicago .  White corn for July delivery, the most active contract on
the South African Futures Exchange, rose 7 rand, or 0.5 percent,
to 1,527 rand ($221) a metric ton as of 9:16 a.m. in
Johannesburg. Meal made from the grain is the country’s staple
food.  Corn for May delivery rose 1.75 cents, or 0.3 percent, to
close yesterday at $6.66 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade,
for the first gain since March 3 on speculation  Japan  will step
up grain purchases once ports and milling plants resume
operations following last week’s deadly earthquake and tsunami.
The contract retreated 0.3 percent in electronic trading today.  In South Africa, yellow corn for July delivery gained 3
rand, or 0.2 percent, to 1,567 rand a ton. The country mainly
uses the grain as  animal feed .  Wheat for May delivery increased 13 rand, or 0.4 percent,
to 3,000 rand a ton.  Gains or losses for the most active contracts of three
additional crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
and the crops are sold per ton:  To contact the reporter on this story:
